@flexiarg peeragogy/newcomer
@title Treat Newcomer Arrival as Renewing Pressure on the Project
@keywords newcomer, beginner-mind, onboarding, audience, regeneration
@audience peer-learning facilitators, contributors
@tone practical
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/wrapper peeragogy/heartbeat peeragogy/creating-a-guide]

! conclusion: A peer-learning project needs newcomers — not only because they extend the community, but because their arrival is the recurring pressure that keeps the project's vocabulary, guides, and onboarding paths from going stale.  Without newcomers, much of the "education stuff" loses its addressee.  Even in the absence of actual newcomers, the project benefits from a *beginner's-mind* perspective applied periodically to its own surfaces.
  + context: Peer-learning projects are written-for-someone, and when no actual newcomer is in earshot, that someone slowly becomes "ourselves a year ago" — a fictional reader who shares all the project's assumptions.  The guide rots, the onboarding path silts up, and the project's accessibility decays without anyone noticing.  The newcomer pattern is the disciplined opposite: every actual newcomer is treated as a probe of the project's current accessibility, and even when none are present, someone periodically reads the project's surfaces with a beginner's mind.  Closely paired with peeragogy/wrapper (the integrative function that makes orientation cheap) and with peeragogy/heartbeat (the rhythm a newcomer can attach to).
  + TENSION:
    Axis: newcomer accommodation ↔ in-group progress.
    Real: every onboarding interaction costs the existing contributors time and attention that could be spent on direct project work.  But the project depends on newcomer flow for its long-term legibility, vocabulary refresh, and energy.  Both costs are real.
    Irreducible: a project cannot simultaneously optimise for fastest in-group progress and lowest newcomer entry cost.  Each onboarding interaction is a deliberate slowing of the in-group pace in exchange for a chance at renewal.
    Active: the pull recurs whenever a newcomer arrives, whenever a long-tenured member catches themselves using shorthand only insiders understand, and whenever the project considers writing a new guide section (since "what would a newcomer need here?" is the live test).
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Mentor-pair on arrival: a named existing contributor accompanies the newcomer through their first contribution rather than handing them documentation.  High-cost, high-yield; converts arrival into participation.
    (2) Newcomer-as-editor: invite the newcomer to edit guide pages, since their inability to follow them is exactly the diagnostic signal needed to fix them.  Combines onboarding with project maintenance.
    (3) Beginner's-mind sweep: in the absence of actual newcomers, a contributor periodically reads the project's onboarding path as if seeing it for the first time and records what is unclear.
    (4) Newcomer-friendly entry tasks: maintain a small set of well-scoped first contributions that a newcomer can accomplish in one sitting, signalling that the project expects their participation early.
    (5) Pair with the wrapper role: the newcomer benefits most when the project has someone summarising current state (wrapper); these two patterns reinforce each other.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: newcomers complete a meaningful first contribution within a short window of arrival, and the project's onboarding surfaces are revised in response to their experience.  Failing when: newcomers either bounce off or take many weeks of unsupported effort to find their way in.
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Audience drift: the project's prose increasingly addresses an in-group reader who already shares all assumptions, with no path for outsiders to enter.
    - Onboarding dead-ends: documented entry paths lead to broken links, abandoned forums, or current contributors no one knows how to reach.
    - Tacit-knowledge moats: every meaningful contribution requires knowledge that lives only in private conversation among long-tenured members.
    - Vocabulary calcification: the project's shared terms stop being interrogated because no one new is around to ask what they mean.
